- identify research direction and develop conceptual ideas;
- understand personal strength and weakness, thus to develop necessary skills to cope with objectives in graduation project;
- build and polish presentation skill in art, thus develop a professional attitude; and

- produce an artwork for graduation exhibition

After completing this course, students will be able to:
- understand major traditional and modern research methodolgy in Chinese art history;
- apply different research methods to conducting art historical research;
- recognize major bibliographical works; and
- acquire skills in finding out research material with the the help of bibliographies.

After completing this course, students will be able to
- understand thoroughly certain special areas in the history of art;
- identify key research topics, questions, scholars and their arguments related to the special areas concerned;
- critically evaluate the validity of different arguments; and
- write academic essay.

After completing this course, students will be able to
- analyze the visual features as well as the philosophical, aesthetic and cultural significance of Chinese literati painting;
- evaluate critically the validity of different arguments concerning a work of Chinese literati painting;
- make use of different research approaches and methodologies in conducting independent research; and
- write academic papers on Chinese literati painting.

After completing this course, students will be able to:
- identify and critically engage with theories of representation informed by multiple disciplines;
- articulate and debate issues regarding culture and the politics of identity;
- apply such theories and issues in everyday cultural life
- design research questions regarding the interpretation and evaluation of contemporary art in culture; and
- propose, structure and articulate arguments and debates in writing.

After completing the course, students will be able to:
1. have a good understanding of major artistic traditions of China, such as pottery, jade, bronze, porcelain, and painting;
2. identify the material properties, production techniques, masterpieces and their producers, key research topics and methods of major artistic traditions;
3. analyze academic articles and arguments of Chinese art history;
4. present Chinese works of art and their historical significance academically;
5. write academic essays on topics of Chinese art history.

After completing the course, students will be able to:
1. Identify and critique key research methods employed in modern and contemporary Asian art;
2. Use the comparative approach to analyse key debates, aesthetic criteria, and cultural differences in modern and contemporary Asian art;
3. Differentiate and explain advanced theoretical frameworks relevant to the field of global contemporary art;
4. Apply theoretical frameworks and methods relevant to Asian modern and contemporary art in research papers and advanced projects such as curation and exhibition catalogues.

After completing the course, students will be able to:
1. identify the distinctive features of paintings from China, Japan, and Korea and the historical contexts that shaped these artworks;
2. examine the impact of cross-border interactions on the evolution of painting styles, themes, techniques, and theories across East Asia;
3. assess the contributions of various social groups, including the imperial and royal courts, scholars, monks, and collectors, to the patronage, circulation, and preservation of paintings in China, Japan, and Korea;
4. recognize the uniqueness of the East Asian artistic network.

After completing the course, students will be able to:
1. have a basic understanding of the development of Chinese ceramics and its unique craft and cultural achievements in the 16th to 19th centuries;
2. know some of the most important examples that show the encounter and exchange of culture, art, science and technology between China and the world using ceramics as a medium;
3. identify some of the most famous pieces of ceramics produced in China and their target markets;
4. recognise some of the most iconic elements from the themes, patterns and forms of ceramic pieces and gain a general idea of their cultural origins;
5. form a scholarly opinion on global fashion trends in ceramic art during the 16th to 19th centuries and their relationship to political and historical events;
6. develop skills in handling objects, interpreting exhibitions, writing academic essays and presenting to the public.

After completing the course, students will be able to:
1. understand the basic theories of art curation and communication;
2. identify the different backgrounds and characteristics of public and private museums, commercial galleries, auction houses, and virtual museums where Chinese art and antiquities are curated;
3. critically examine curatorial concepts behind the display of Chinese art and antiquities;
4. reflect on various strategies for conveying knowledge and concepts of Chinese art and antiquities to contemporary audience.

After completing the course, students will be able to:
1. understand the whole development of the Chinese calligraphy from the pre-Qin periods to the twentieth century;
2. recognize key calligraphic masterpieces;
3. analyze the visual features as well as the aesthetic, social and cultural significance of Chinese calligraphy;
4. evaluate critically the validity of different arguments concerning a work of Chinese calligraphy; and
5. write academic papers on Chinese calligraphy.

After completing the course, students will be able to:
1. analyze important works of painting, sculpture, and architecture created by each Buddhist tradition in different parts of Asia;
2. identify regional variances, trans-regional diffusions, inter-regional commonalities, and historical transformations among cultures of the pan-Buddhist world;
3. recognize the function and meaning of key Buddhist art and artefacts in the religious settings;
4. understand philosophy of Buddhism and its historical development;
5. develop skills in writing academic essays.

After completing the course, students will be able to:
1. gain a comprehensive understanding of ancient Chinese bronzes, exploring their artistic, technological, and cultural significance;
2. develop critical analysis skills to appreciate the role of bronzes in affecting the development of Chinese culture, ritual, and civilization;
3. act as active observers and thinkers, engaging thoughtfully with the artistic expressions found in ancient bronzes;
4. acquire essential research skills that prepare students for advanced studies in art history, with a focus on ancient Chinese artifacts.

After completing the course, students will be able to:
1. identify the histories and theories of media art and moving image art in Asia;
2. elaborate on major media art movements from the Enlightenment to the 21st century;
3. apply major theories of media art history to research papers and curatorial projects;
4. identify key conservation issues of media art in museums;
5. employ various approaches to analysing the analogue and digital media.

After completing the course, students will be able to:
1. become familiar with English terminology in major areas of Chinese art history;
2. read and critically analyse art historical essays;
3. identify key components and structure of art historical writings for different purposes;
4. compose catalogue entries and an argumentative article on Chinese art objects in English.
